2. How a 'UPDATE' statment run in background ?

=> ✅ 1. Client Side -
	----------------------
		You write -

		UPDATE employees SET salary = salary + 500 WHERE id = 101;

	✅ 2. Listener & Server Process Creation  -
	---------------------------------------------
		Listener receives the connection request and assigns a server process (Dedicated or Shared Server mode).

		The server process handles all SQL execution for your session.

	✅ 3. Parsing Phase (Library Cache in Shared Pool) -
	---------------------------------------------------

			When your query reaches the Oracle Instance:

			Check Library Cache (Shared Pool in SGA):

			If an identical query already exists → reuse execution plan.

			If not → hard parse.

			SQL Parser:

			Checks SQL syntax and semantics (are tables/columns valid? do you have privileges?).

			Optimizer (CBO):

			Creates an execution plan (how to find the rows efficiently).

			Row Source Tree:

			A set of steps the engine will follow to perform the update.

	✅ 4. Execution Phase -
	----------------------

			Server process starts executing the plan:

			Reads required data blocks into Database Buffer Cache (from Datafiles if not already cached).

			Applies Row-Level Exclusive Locks (TX locks) on the rows to be updated (so no one else can modify them until commit).

	✅ 5. Modification in Memory -
	----------------------

			The new salary value is applied to the copy of the block in the Database Buffer Cache (SGA).

			The undo tablespace is updated with the before image of the data (for rollback or read consistency).

			Redo entries are generated in the Redo Log Buffer (SGA) — they describe the change, not the data itself.

	✅ 6. Commit Phase -
	----------------------

			When you execute: 'COMMIT;'

			LGWR immediately writes all redo from Redo Log Buffer to disk.

			Locks are released.

			Change becomes permanent and visible to others.

	🔍🔍 Key Points for UPDATE in Oracle Architecture -
	----------------------------------------------------

			Parsing & Optimization happen in Shared Pool.

			Actual data change happens in memory first (Buffer Cache).

			Redo logs guarantee recoverability.

			Undo data ensures rollback and read consistency.

			DBWR doesn’t write immediately — it’s lazy; LGWR writes immediately on commit.

