## PMON (Process Monitor):
------------------------------
✅ PMON is responsible for -  process recovery when a user process fails/crash, It cleans up resources Free the spaces.

✅ Simple Definition:

👉 "Jab koi 'User Process' unexpectedly fail/crash ho jaaye — toh PMON us process ka cleanup karta hai automatically."

👉 "PMON failed user processes ka cleanup karta hai — uncommitted transactions rollback karta hai, locks release karta hai, resources free karta hai, aur services listener mein register karta hai."

👉 Service names ko - LISTENER mein register karta hai, Taaki naye clients database se connect kar sakein.

User ka session crash hua
(Network cut / App crash / Laptop band)
          │
          ▼
PMON detect karta hai
          │
          ├── 1. Uncommitted transactions
          │       → ROLLBACK karta hai
          │
          ├── 2. Locks jo us process ne
          │   liye the
          │       → RELEASE karta hai
          │
          ├── 3. SGA memory jo allocate
          │   thi us process ke liye
          │       → FREE karta hai
          │
          └── 4. Server Process
                  → Terminate karta hai

## SMON (System Monitor):
------------------------------
✅ SMON performs instance recovery at startup, team-up/linked-up free space in the database, and cleans up temporary segments that are no longer in use.

✅ Simple Definition:

👉"SMON System Monitor hai — iska main kaam Instance Recovery hai jisme do phases hote hain: 
Roll Forward - jisme Redo Logs se committed data recover hota hai, aur 
Roll Back - jisme UNDO se uncommitted transactions rollback hote hain. 
Saath mein SMON Temp Segment cleanup aur Free Space Coalescing bhi karta hai."


SMON
  │
  ├── 1. Instance Recovery
  ├── 2. Temp Segment Cleanup
  └── 3. Free Space Coalescing

## DBWn (Database Writer):
------------------------------
✅ There are multiple DBWn processes (DBW0, DBW1, etc.). They are responsible for writing 
	modified blocks from the database buffer cache to the data files on disk.

## LGWR (Log Writer):
------------------------------
✅ LGWR writes redo entries from the redo log buffer to the redo log files. Redo logs are 
	crucial for database recovery and transaction durability.

## CKPT (Checkpoint):
------------------------------
✅ CKPT instruct DBwn to write dirty block into the datafiles (Committed + Uncommitted both). update control file with SCN number. And, update Datafile Headers.

🟢 Full Checkpoint - Buffer Cache ke SARE dirty blocks ek saath Datafiles pe likho — ABHI!
	 Kab hota hai - 
		1. Database SHUTDOWN hone pe
		2. ALTER SYSTEM CHECKPOINT; (Manual)
		3. ALTER TABLESPACE BEGIN BACKUP;
		4. Log Switch hone pe (older versions)

🟢 Incremental Checkpoint - Continuously — thode thode dirty blocks likhte raho background 
	 mein — smoothly!

✅ Checkpoint Information :

👉 Checkpoint SCN (System Change Number)
👉 Datafile header update
👉 Control file update
👉 Recovery ke liye reference point

During a checkpoint, Oracle ensures that all dirty buffers (modified blocks in the Database Buffer Cache) are written to the data files, and it records checkpoint information in the control file and data file headers.

