=> ✅ Read consistency means: when you read data, Oracle shows you a clean and stable version of the data, even if other users are changing it at the same time.
------------------------------------------------------------------------

10. Difference between UNDO and REDO ?

=> ✅ UNDO :	🔹 Stores the old data before a change
			   	🔹 Used for ROLLBACK and read consistency

	✅ REDO :  	🔹 Helps Oracle re-apply changes after a crash
			     	🔹 Used for recovery, not rollback
------------------------------------------------------------------------

11. Purpose of PGA, SGA components ?

=> ✅ PGA : 	🔹 When an SQL executes PGA store a private workspace for each session/users, 
						so the query will execute smoothly.
					🔹 It also used for Sorting (ORDER BY, GROUP BY) activity.

	🔹 Important PGA components :-  Private SQL Area, Session Memory, Sort Area, Stack Space

	✅ SGA : 	🔹 SGA stores shared data and control information needed by the entire database when instance starts. 

	🔹 Important SGA components :-  Database Buffer Cache, Shared Pool, Redo Log Buffer,Large 
											  Pool (optional), Java Pool, Streams Pool.
------------------------------------------------------------------------

12. When SGA got created ?

=> ✅ The SGA is created during database startup, at the NOMOUNT stage.

		🔹 NOMOUNT stage  ← SGA is created here

			Oracle:

			👉 Reads spfile / pfile

			👉 Allocates SGA memory

			👉 Starts background processes (SMON, PMON, DBWR, LGWR, CKPT, etc.)

			👉 At this point:

			👉 SGA exists

			👉 Control files not yet read

			👉 Database not yet mounted

------------------------------------------------------------------------

13. In which condition UGA not creted inside PGA ?

=> ✅ UGA is NOT created inside PGA when the database is using SHARED SERVER mode.

	🔹 Why this happens :

		👉 In Dedicated Server, Each user has one dedicated server process.
		👉 PGA belongs to that server process.
		👉 So UGA is stored inside PGA.

		In Shared Server, 

		👉 Server processes are shared among many users.
		👉 A shared server cannot keep session state in its PGA.

			Therefore,

		👉 UGA is moved to SGA.
		👉 Stored in Large Pool.
		👉 Or Shared Pool if Large Pool is not configured.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

14. Purpose of SGA  ? (which kind of process in SGA cover)

=> ✅ SGA is a shared memory area for every session/users that oracle use to run the databse effecient and safety.

		It exists so that:--

		🔹 Data does not need to be read from disk again and again
		🔹 SQL statements can be reused
		🔹 Changes can be recovered after a crash
		🔹 Multiple users can work at the same time
------------------------------------------------------------------------

13. Diffrence between PGA & UGA ?

=> ✅ The PGA (Program Global Area) is a 'private workspace' in memory for each users/
		sessions which connected to the Oracle database.

		🔹 Sort area
		🔹 Hash join area
		🔹 Cursor execution state

	✅ UGA: (User Global Area) is memory that stores session-related information. 
		UGA is stored inside PGA.
		
		🔹 Login/session info
		🔹 Session variables
		🔹 Cursor state
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

14. Purpose of Redo Log Files ?

=> ✅ Main purpose is, Oracle can recover data when database crashed. Redo log keep all the 			recored that changes to the database. So, if database got crashed it can start recovery
		process. instance recovery.

		👉 Without redo logs, Oracle cannot recover committed data after a crash.

	✅ How redo logs are used (step-by-step) :

		👉 Redo is written for every change, not only at COMMIT
		👉 Changes are made in Database Buffer Cache
		👉 Redo information is generated and placed in Redo Log Buffer
		👉 On COMMIT, LGWR writes redo buffer to redo log files (disk)
		👉 After a crash, Oracle uses redo log file to recover
		👉 Oracle re-applies all changes found in redo log file (roll forward)
		👉 Then UNDO recovery rolls back uncommitted transactions

	💥 If database crashes -> Instance Recovery happens:

		🔹 Step 1️. Roll Forward (REDO) :

			👉 SMON reads redo log files.
			👉 Re-applies all changes (committed + uncommitted).

		🔹 Step 2️ Roll Back (UNDO recovery) :

			👉 Oracle uses UNDO.
			👉 Keep only commited changes.
			👉 Removes uncommitted changes.
			👉 Releases locks.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

15. What is UNDO Read Consistency?

=> ✅ UNDO read consistency means - 'Oracle uses UNDO data to show you the old value when
		 someone else fetch the same data at the same time using select statment.

	✅ Simple real-life example -

		👉 User A -- UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 1000 WHERE id = 1; -- not committed
		👉 User B (at the same time) -- SELECT balance FROM accounts WHERE id = 1;
		👉 User B sees the old balance, not the changed one.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------

16. What is UNDO Retaintion policy ?

=> ✅ UNDO retention policy means how long Oracle try to keep old data (undo information) 
		before reusing it.

		"Commit hone ke BAAD bhi, UNDO data ko kitni der tak preserve rakha jaaye — yahi UNDO Retention Policy hai." (15 minites)

		"Commit hone ke baad bhi, UNDO data ko kam se kam 900 seconds (15 minites) tak mat delete karo."

	✅	Parameter:
		👉 UNDO_RETENTION = 900 seconds (default — 15 minutes)

	✅ UNDO_RETENTION parameter --
		👉 SHOW PARAMETER undo_retention;

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
16. Purpose of SYSTEM Tablespace ?

=> ✅ SYSTEM tablespace stores the 'data dictionary' or 'meta deta', Without it database 
		can not start. It is mandatory and critical.

	✅ What is stored in SYSTEM tablespace --

		👉 It stores metadata such as, Tables, indexes, views definitions
		👉 Users and roles
		👉 Privileges
		👉 Tablespaces and datafiles
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

17. Where the meta data present in memory ?

=> ✅ Metadata is physically stored in the SYSTEM tablespace (on disk) and,
		 cached in memory in the Data Dictionary Cache inside the Shared Pool (SGA).
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

18. What is Soft parsing and Hard parsing ?

=> ✅ Soft parsing -- Same SQL text already exists in Library Cache. Oracle reuses an 
								existing execution plan from the Shared Pool.

	✅ Hard parsing -- Newly SQL text that doesn't exists in Library Cache. Oracle creates 
								a new execution plan for the SQL statement.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

19. Do soft parsing need syntax and semantic checks? and why?

=> ✅ Yes, soft parsing still requires some checks, but they are minimal.

	🧠 Why any checks are needed --

		👉 Even if Oracle reuses an execution plan, it must still ensure The SQL is still valid.
		👉 The user is allowed or not to run it.
		👉 The objects involved still exist or not. Otherwise, Oracle could return wrong or unauthorized data.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

